<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">Mechanisms are explanations of the causal 
 relationship between two Events. &nbsp;They 
 contain reusable signals which are used to calculate the probabilities 
 that Events occur. </p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">There are two types of Mechanisms: </p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<ol 	type=1>
	
	<li  class="kadov-p"><p class="hcp3"><a  href="Drill_Down/Mechanism_Types/Cause.htm"
	id=a1>Causes</a></p></li>
	
	<li  class="kadov-p"><p class="hcp3"><a  href="Drill_Down/Mechanism_Types/Inhibitor.htm"
	id=a4>Inhibitors</a> </p></li>
</ol>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">To create a Mechanism between two Events, 
 click on the Add Mechanism button <img src="image24.gif"
										

										width=22
										height=22
										border="0"> in the Model Toolbar. 
 &nbsp;Next, click 
 on the Event which is creating the effect, and drag the arrow to the Event 
 which is being affected. &nbsp;<a href="Drill_Down/Mechanism_Types/Mechanism_Type2.htm"
	title="Click here to view the Mechanism dialog box."
	id=a2>A dialog box will appear</a>:</p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">You now need to enter in the name of the 
 Mechanism and select if it’s a Cause Mechanism or an Inhibitor Mechanism. 
 &nbsp;First, 
 click on the check box corresponding to the Mechanism type you want. &nbsp;Next, 
 you can either create a new name for your Mechanism or you can use a predetermined 
 one already in your Model. &nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">To create a new name, enter the name in 
 the Mechanism Name text field and click on the “Create New” button. &nbsp;To 
 reuse an earlier name, click on the name you want from the Available Signals 
 display and click on the “Use Predefined” button.</p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">An Event can receive multiple signals with 
 the same name as long as the signals are either all Causes or all Inhibitors. 
 &nbsp;It can 
 also send out both Causes and Inhibitors with the same name. &nbsp;However, 
 it cannot receive a Causal signal and an Inhibitor signal with the same 
 name.</p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
<p class="hcp2">To modify how a signal affects an Event, 
 right click on the Event and enter the “Edit Event” dialog.</p>
<p class="hcp2">&nbsp;</p>
